<Page x:Class="AsynAwaitExamples.Steps.Step19_WhenEach"
      xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml/presentation"
      xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml"
      xmlns:vm="clr-namespace:AsynAwaitExamples.ViewModels"
      Title="Step 19 - Task.WhenEach">
    <Page.DataContext>
        <vm:Step19ViewModel/>
    </Page.DataContext>
    <ScrollViewer VerticalScrollBarVisibility="Auto">
        <StackPanel Margin="10">
            <TextBlock Style="{StaticResource HeaderStyle}" 
                       Text="Step 19: Task.WhenEach (.NET 9+)"/>

            <TextBlock Style="{StaticResource ExplanationStyle}" xml:space="preserve">WHENEACH: Process tasks in the order they COMPLETE (not the order you started them).

Task.WhenAll waits for ALL tasks, then gives you all results at once.
Task.WhenAny gives you the FIRST completed task (but you have to loop manually).
Task.WhenEach (new in .NET 9) returns an IAsyncEnumerable that yields tasks
in completion order. Use "await foreach" to process them!

This is much cleaner than the old "WhenAny in a loop" pattern, and it gives
a better user experience: results appear on screen as soon as they are ready.</TextBlock>

            <Button Style="{StaticResource ActionButton}"
                    Content="[1] Process tasks in completion order"
                    Command="{Binding WhenEachDemoCommand}"/>
            <Button Style="{StaticResource ActionButton}"
                    Content="[2] Compare WhenAll vs WhenEach UX"
                    Command="{Binding CompareWhenAllVsWhenEachCommand}"/>
            <Button Style="{StaticResource ActionButton}"
                    Content="[3] WhenEach with error handling"
                    Command="{Binding WhenEachWithErrorsCommand}"/>

            <TextBox Style="{StaticResource OutputStyle}" Height="300"
                     Text="{Binding OutputText, Mode=OneWay}"/>
        </StackPanel>
    </ScrollViewer>
</Page>
